    "Hash-based methods provide theoretical guarantees on query accuracy and are the only SotA approximate methods that support theoretical guarantees on query performance.",
    "However, building the index requires a significant overhead both in space and time, often requiring different indexes to beAlgorithm 1: Beam Search (G, 𝑉 𝑄, s, k, L) Input: Graph G, query vector 𝑉 𝑄, initial seeds s, result size k, beam width L ≥ k Output: k approximate nearest neighbors to 𝑉 𝑄 1 initialize candidate set C ←-s; 2 initialize visited list R ←-∅; 3 while C\\R ≠ ∅ do 4 let 𝑝 * ←-argmin 𝑉 𝑖 ∈C\\R 𝑑𝑖𝑠𝑡 𝑉 𝑄, 𝑉 𝑖; 5 update C ←-C ∪ 𝑁 𝑜𝑢𝑡 (𝑝 *); 6 update R ←-R ∪ 𝑝 *; 7 if |C| > L then 8 update C to retain closest L points to 𝑉 𝑄; 9 return the k candidates in C closest to 𝑉 𝑄;pre-built to support different guarantees during search.",
